        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(ollama): release stream reader lock to prevent resource leak",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n**What problem does this PR solve?**\n\n- Fix classification: Defensive reader-lock release in the native Ollama stream cleanup block.\n- Root cause: `stream.ts:1465` finally block calls `release()` (fetch guard) but never `reader.releaseLock()`. The established codebase pattern in `http-error-body.ts:11`, `provider-http-errors.ts:44`, and `voice-call/response-body.ts:28` calls both `reader.cancel()` AND `reader.releaseLock()` in finally blocks.\n- Why this is pattern-match fix: This PR brings the Ollama stream reader in line with the existing codebase convention — no new pattern invented, just applying the same defensive lock-release already used elsewhere.\n- Patch quality notes: 3 lines added. Purely defensive — `cancel()` already releases the lock implicitly in most engines.\n\n**Why does this matter now?**\n\n- Consistency: Every other stream-reader finally block in the codebase releases the lock. Ollama was the outlier.\n\n**What is intentionally out of scope?**\n\n- Does NOT change: fetch-guard `release()`, stream data flow, error handling, abort behavior, or the reader read-loop logic.\n\n**What should reviewers focus on?**\n\n- Pattern consistency: Compare with `http-error-body.ts:11`, `provider-http-errors.ts:44`, `voice-call/response-body.ts:28` — all follow the same `cancel() + releaseLock()` pattern this PR applies to Ollama.",
